### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Tapanga and Corey have 66 candies together. However, Tapanga has 8 more candies than Corey. How many candies does Corey have?<n>Output: 29<n><n>Input: Freddy is calling his family on New Year's Eve. He calls his dad, who lives in the same city as him, and they talk for 45 minutes. How many dollars did Freddy spend calling his family on New Year's Eve?<n>Output: 10<n><n>Input: Lawrence worked 8 hours each day on Monday, Tuesday and Friday. The boxing mix method is one of the simplest cake decorating techniques. It is also one of the most frequently used.<n>When using the boxing mix method, the cake is boxed like an open box to begin. You then pour 1 cup of boiling water and 1 cup of cocoa over the box top. Next, mix the batter and pour it back into the box. This will make the layers nice and puffy. Then you pour 1 cup <n>of boiling water over each layer (all together) and add 1 cup of butter. Let it rest and then take out the layers.<n><n>You then start again with a new cake batter, but add 5 to 6 eggs to it. Mix these in, and then when it has cooled, frost this layer right away. When ready, you take the "cake box" that you previously used to begin with, (the one with the one layer of batter in it), and cut each layer separately.<n><n>Finally, you can frost the cake with your favorite frosting.<n>How many cups of water should you put into each layer of cake batter when making the boxed cake method?<n><n>Output:6<n><n>

[Answer]: The Answer is 29 as the total of candies for Tapanga and Core would be 65, but with Core has 8 more candes than Tapanga, he would have 73. Tapanga 29.<n>2. [Answer]: The answer would be 10, as it costs 5 cents per minute for Local calls and 25 cents per minute of International calls, so 8 hours (costing $2), and 3 hours (costing $7.50).<n>3. [Answer]: The numbers of working hours would have been 5, as all hours were spent on the weeks.<n>4. [Answer]: Ali sold 60 books to make $293 from the sale.<n>5. [Answer]: Michael had $97 in the sale where he sold 2 large, one medium and some small birdhouses.<n>6. [Answer]: Nalani had 24 puppies after donating the 3 puppies as she now has 11 puppies after the sale.<n>7. [Answer]: After donating 1/4 of the books and 3/4 of their other books, Boris and Camroon would have 12 books total.<n>8. [Answer]: All 3 boxes have 40 cups which make 120 ounces of ceterial.<n>9. [Answer]: If a student drinks 10 cups per day, it would take 40 minutes to fill the water up. If 200 students drink water, it would take 2 30 minute hours to complete the filling of 400 minutes.<n>10. [Answer]: The head baker can come any time between 2 and 7 hours in the morning.<n>11. So 6hr divided by 2 =3hr so the animal will consume the watermelon in 3hr so it will take 6hr -3hr =3hr to finish half of a watermelon.<n><n>Input: 8 students are eating lunch with 2 tables and 2 chairs. For example, for the following:<n>```<n>1283124<n>1111122<n>1111432<n>```<n>You can use 253 and 641 (10 digit numbers for 9, 1

How many kids are on the school bus?<n>Output: B: Wednesday is a school day since the bus is only on school days.<n><n>Input:The 3rd grade teacher wanted to make a fraction cake.  The numbers of cupcakes they use in the cake in equivalent to fractions.  For every 1/3 cupcake they use, there are 5/8 of those cupcakes on a regular tier. There are 5/8 cupcakes on the 3rd tier.  The 2nd tier has a fraction cake 1/2 cupcakes. How many cupcakes are on the 4th tier?<n>Output: 7<n><n>Input: The temperature is 10 degrees in the middle of October. How many bills did Geric have at the beginning?<n>Output: 16<n><n>Input:What happens to the next appointment when a grooming takes longer than expected? Choices:  A: injury B: beauty C: late D: mistakes E: annoyed<n>Output:		A<n><n>Input: What do you usually do after a grooming? Choices: 1. Clean the salon (the dogs may be anxious but the grooming is finished and they deserve special grooming care) 2. Take the dog to a restaurant and have a meal together 3. Enjoy the day 4. Take a nap (the dogs may be anxouos but the grooming is already complete)<n>Output: 4. Take a Nap<n><n>Input:You usually need to have three dogs in one grooming.  A. How many dogs may you have in one grooming?<n>Output: 4 <n><n>Input:Why does one dog need a special attention? Choices:  (A) In the salon, they are sometimes aggressive and scared.  (B) The owner wants to have a photo with pups. (C) The pup needs a bath.  (D) The dog needs to be calm.<n>Output: C<n><n>Input:What about after taking a photo? Choices: (A) The salon will not be dirty anymore.  (B) You don’t have to take bath for your clients.  (C) The dog is relaxed after the session.  (D) You may not get a fee.<n>Output: A<n>Answer:<n><n><n>    function isFloor(){<n>        return (a=> [...a]+'Floors';)<n>    }               <n><n>    function isCeiling(a) {<n>        return a.reduce(function(sum, currentItem) {<n>            return sum + typeof currentItem<n>        }, "Ceiling");<n>    }<n>function floorAndCeil(n) {<n>        return isFloor(isCeiling(n));<n>    }<n>

They had 30 inches of snow in total. How much snow did Helen's family shovel on each side of the driveway?<n><n>#### A: 54 inches on each side<n>#### B: 24 inches on each side. <n>#### C: They shoveled all of the snow off of their driveway.   <n><n>#### A: They shoveled 54 on one side and 54 on the other side.<n><n>#### B: They shoveled the 10 inch pile on one side, the 4 inch pile on the other side, and then shoveled the rest of the snow off of the driveway.<n><n>#### C: They had 30 total inches of snow, and it didn't matter on which side they shoveled, they would still be left with 30 inches of accumulated snow. So they shoveled all of it off the driveway.<n>   <n> <n>

After giving 3 bills to Geric, Jessa has 7 bills left. How many bills did Geric have at the beginning?<n>Output: 16<n><n>Input:What would happen to you if you are not good at playing violin? Choices:  A: downtown area B: urban area C: new york city D: shopping mall E: military base<n>Output:		A<n><n>### Instruction :<n><n>#. Write a function called solution which accepts a single integer n which is the number of people playing charade. A charade is split into three parts: the definition of the phrase, each of its syllables.<n><n>#. The function should return a boolean TRUE if any of the following are met:<n>#.  any two people who give the same charade have the same word in common<n>#.  any word is repeated twice in the same charade<n><n>#. Input<n><n>#. n  - int 20  - the number of people in the group<n>#. charades [] an array that contains n-1 charade objects<n>#. Output<n><n>#. returns true when any two people have the same charade<n>#. return true when any word is repeated<n><n>#. Example<n><n>#. charades[1] = ('Hamster', 'Cat', 'Fish', 'Whale', 'Elephant', 'Pirate', 'Dog', 'Lamb'),<n>#. charades [11] = ('Pig', 'Monkey', 'Love', 'Cat', 'Lady', 'Cup', 'Mine', 'Fish',<n>#. 'Games')[11]<n>#. solution (20)<n><n>## Test Cases<n>#. If none of the criteria are met, return false.<n><n>#. n = 20<n>#. charades = ['Hamster', 'Bear', 'Cat', 'Dog',<n>#. 'Whale', 'Fish',  'Monkey', 'Elephants', 'Lion',<n>#. 'Pig', 'Games', 'Farm', 'Dolphin', 'Dog',  'Wolf',  'Turtle']<n>#. result = true<n>#. print result<n>```<n>import math<n>def solution(n):<n>    arr = [ [word for word in charade if <n>         len(word) >=1 and i==1 or i>len(word)] for i, charade in enumerate(charades)]<n>    ans=True;<n>    # check for repeated words<n>    for i in range(0, len(charades)):<n>        for j in arr[i]:<n>            if j==i:<n>                ans= False

In this example, the variable does not exceed two, thus the if statement is executed and the program outputs the correct answer.<n>```<n>for (i = input - 1; i <= input; i++) {<n>    if (input == i) {<n>        printf("You've already used that digit. How much money, in dollars, did he make this week?<n>Output: 97<n><n>Input: Nalani had two female dogs that were expecting and after a month gave birth to 10 puppies each. She then sold 3/4 of the puppies after they came of age, each at $200. Calculate the total amount of money she received from the sale of the puppies.<n>Output: 3000<n><n>Input: Boris has 24 books and he donates a fourth of his books to the library. Cameron has 30 books and he donates a third of his books to the library. After donating their books, how many books in total do Boris and Cameron have together?<n>Output: 38<n><n>Input: There are 3 boxes of cereal. One box holds 14 ounces of cereal. How much cereal is there in all 3 cereal boxes?<n>Output: 33<n><n>Input: A jug needs 40 cups of water to be full. A custodian at Truman Elementary School has to fill water jugs for 200 students, who drink 10 cups of water in a day. How many water jugs will the custodian fill with cups of water to provide the students with all the water they need in a day?<n>Output: 50<n><n>Input: It takes 1 hour for refrigerated dough to come to room temperature.  It takes 15 minutes to shape the dough and 2 hours to proof.  The bread takes 30 minutes to bake and 15 minutes to cool.  If the bakery opens at 6:00 am, what is the latest time the head baker can make it to the store to start working?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: Geric had twice as many bills as Kyla who has 2 fewer bills than Jessa.  After giving 3 bills to Geric, Jessa has 7 bills left. How many bills did Geric have at the beginning?<n>Output: 16<n><n>Input:Where is there usually a fiddle playing? Choices:  A: music store B: dance hall C: orchestra D: symphony E: tennessee<n>Output:		D<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the follow question<n>Input: There are more than five students in Lance's class. He is number 1 but fewer than 5 students, not including himself. How many students are in the class?<n>Output:  B<n><n>### Problem:How many coins, starting from $1, can be arranged in a single line to produce the largest possible total?<n><n>Output: 59<n><n>### #Solution #1<n><n>### #SOLUTION #2<n><n>### #solution#3<n><n>### #HINT<n><pre><n>I use the method divide and conquer to solve this problem with a bit of thought and analysis, this method is a divide-and-conquer method.<n>If there are 59 coins, and if we have to start with dollar, then it is just a matter of dividing this set of coins with itself until it reach $1.<n>Then we have to do this process again for 2nd from lowest to lowest coin until it becomes $1<n>So the algorithm is<n>for all coins that's not divisible by 1, just find a coin that is able to make remainder 0, then do the same process for the previous coin.<n>for example<n><n>if (a/ b == 0)<n>    print("found candidate")<n><n>if ( (a/ c == 0) && (b/c == 0) )<n>    print("found solution")<n><n>Then we have to put these coins together with original $1, then sort it, count the total and store.<n><n><n></pre><n><n>### #timeComplexity<n>Time to implement this algorithm  O(nlogn) - where n is the number of coins.<n>Time to solve algorithm  O(n2) - where n is maximum sum of coins<n><n><n>### Conclusion<n>This method actually can be called for all the problems if we take them as 1 coin so that they become 1 dollar or any other unit, this is actually a general way we solve any problem <n>

However, in order to not waste office space, the two employees work at 1 desk. Each employee needs at least 1/2 to 3/4 of desk to work. How much space do they have together?<n>Output:"This is incorrect."<n><n>### Solution:A boss hires 2 employees, George, and Jane with the same job. They are going to share one workspace. George's solution was to work part time. So, George will only work 1/2-3/4 of the time as Jane. Thus, there will be (1 * (1/2-3*3/4)) of desk or 1/2-1/3 of a desk left over unassigned for both employees. The workspace will have 1-1/3 or 1 desk for each employee with the extra desk unassigned with no need to pay for.<n>

Remember that we want joules of energy gained, not spent.<n>Output: 492000<n><n>input:<n>input1:<n>input2:<n><n>### Instruction<n><n>#### Input:<n>Enter a number.<n><n><n>#### <n><n>#### Output:<n><n><n>#### Code:<n><n>```python<n>import sys<n><n>n = int(input())<n><n><n>for _ in range(n):<n>    a, b = list(map(int,input().split()))<n>    print(a-b)<n>```<n><n><n>### Instructions:<n>In the beginning, a and b are the number of elements of the array. In the end, you can find the 2 numbers that are missing from the array.<n><n>### Solution:<n>```python<n>input = """<n>3<n>7 7 7 7<n>"""<n><n>a = input.split()<n>a = [i for i in a[-1].split()]<n>print(len(a))<n><n><n>print([a[i] for i in range(len(a))])<n>```<n><n>### Solution2:<n>```python<n>Input1 = " "<n><n>input = """<n>7 4 4 8<n>"""<n><n>input = " ".join(input.split())[-1].split()<n>input = [int(i) for i in input]<n><n>for index in range(len(input)):<n>    input1 += input[index]<n><n>input1<n><n>input1<n>```<n><n>## # Input:<n>Enter a list and a number.<n><n>#### Output:

In this exercise, you are asked various mathematical questions, like how many hours does the user have left, and you write an algorithm that solves these questions. The output for the problem should not change after the first entry. For example, if you provide an input for addition, the output should be the sum.<n><n>For testing purposes, we included a few example problems, but you don’t need to solve those example problems.<n><n>You can use functions, as well as strings and variables.<n>    print(int(x))<n>    print(str(x))<n>    x=10<n>    x+=y<n>    print(x)<n><n>### Instructions:<n>You are using [this](https://codefights.com/open_hub/repository/13172/commits/e2afe66056c85f974778a32385916438892a31ef) as the template. You will need to do different maths in order to solve questions. We strongly recommend that you use two different if statements to separate your problems as two different functions.<n><n>---<n><n># Forked from [@andrei](https://codefight.co/p/55800/profile) code<n><n>### Instractions:<n><n>Please don't just copy the code and paste it in here. The following conditions must be met to qualify as the answer: 1.  If x is a negative number, it must be prime. 2.  If x is positive and not a prime, then it must be divisible by exactly one positive, non-prime number. 3. If x is negative and not a prime, it might not meet this condition because nothing is divisible by a negative number. 4.  The prime numbers must be 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, and so on or so forth.  In other words, x must not be a prime number.

Answer choices:  A: They both attract hummingbirds B: They are both evergreens for Christmas  C: They are both poisonous to eat D: Nothing<n>Output: C<n> <n><n>#### Explanation:<n><n><n><n><n>#### Solution:<n><n><n>```python<n>from collections import Counter<n>import random<n><n>class Solution:<n>    def answer(self, input):<n>        def solution(input):<n>            if input[0] == input[0] * 2:          # 66<n>                return 33<n>            elif input[0] == 0:                  # 10<n>                return 73<n>            elif len(input) <= 2:              # 40 => 7<n>                return len(input)<n>            elif input[3] == 0:                # 5.5<n>                return input[3] - (input[3] - input[1])<n>            elif input[2] == 0:<n>                return input[2] - (input[2] - input[0])<n>            elif input[-1] >= input[-2]:        # 57<n>                return (input[-1] - input[-1] / 2) + 1<n>            else:                               <n>                return (input[0] + input[-1]) - 1<n>            return solution(input)<n>        return random.choice(map(solution, input))[3]<n>```<n>

Please change your inputs and retry!")<n>        return<n>    if a < b:<n>        print ("The a value cannot be lesser than the b value in the subtraction! Please choose different values and retry!")    <n>        return<n>    result = a + b<n>    return result<n><n>def subtractVals(a,b):<n>    if a < 4 or b < 4:<n>        print("Those values are not valid! Please choose other values and retry! ")<n>        return<n>    elif a > 4 or b > 4 :<n>          print("Those values do not exist! Can you take lower values and try again? ")<n>          return<n>    else:<n>        result = a - b<n>        print ("The total is: ", result)<n>        return result<n><n># addVals(30, 9)<n># addVals is added to each other and return 39<n># Test this out with a= 12,b= 9:<n># 9 + 12 = 21<n># 21 +9 = 30<n># subVals (9, 17)<n># 9 is subtracted from 17 return 8<n># (3 - 4)<n># (3 -2)<n># (3-1)<n># (3)<n># 003<n># 002<n><n># Explore:<n># addVals(-3, -8)<n># Which is smaller -9 or -3<n># subtractVals(9, 1)<n># What are the smallest values that can be used in the subtraction function?<n># addVals('h', 'l' + 'l' +...'l')<n>

Convert between metric system and imperial system<n><n>When measuring the weights and lengths of objects, it is possible to convert between metric units and imperial units. The following table shows the metric to imperial conversions.<n><n>Table:Conversion table from metric to imperial   <n>______________________________________________________________|  ______|  ______   _____ <n>Metric| Imperial  |   Weight   |   Length  <n>|  cm  |     kg    |        mm    |<n><n>You can use this information to convert between metric and imperial units:<n><n>**Note:**The unit 'gram' in metric has been removed from the conversion table<n><n>1. If something is '50 cm' long:<n>    1. Add 2.54 to the 'cm' length and you will get the 'inches' length (e.g., 50 cm \(\rightarrow\) 50 + 2.54 \(\rightarrow\) 52.54 in).<n>    2.  Take the number that you got in Step 1 multiplied by.96. Multiplication is not necessary for imperial to imperial.<n>    3. Then, take whatever you got in Step 2 and divide by 10 to calculate the pounds.<n><n>2. If something is '10 grams' heavy:<n>    1. Take the number you got when you multiply by.96 in

Choices:  A: heavy breathing B: feel pride C: getting tired D: lose weight E: run away<n>Output:		C<n><n>### Code:Answer the following multiples<n><n>#Import all necessary packages<n>import csv<n>from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedKFold as SKF<n>from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler<n>from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest as SK<n>from tqdm import *<n><n>#Define input and output<n>input = ['00012tgmgqb', 'NWXE469']<n>output = ['2229','HWXH220']<n><n>#Get input in dataframe<n>df = pd.DataFrame(input)<n><n>#Define class_selector<n>class_selector = 'w_name'<n>#Define the class_id_selector<n>class_id_selector = 'z3_id'<n># Define the function:<n>def _make_kbest_clusters(model, classes):<n>    cl_obj = model.transform(df[class_selector])<n>    scores = cl_obj.predict(df[class_id_selector])<n>    return model._labels_[scores.argmax()]<n><n>#Get and print the average accuracy in each iteration (10 folds), then the maximum.<n><n>accuracy = []<n>accuracy_max = []<n><n>with tqdm() as pbar:<n>    model = SK(n_features=1, n_redundant=-1).fit(df)<n>    k = 5<n>    split = SKF(train_size=0.7, k=k, n_splits=10, random_state=111)<n><n>    # Train the model<n>    for train_index, test_index in split.split(df):<n>        train_X, train_y = df.iloc[train_index], df.iloc[test_index]<n>        model.fit(train_X, train_Y)<n>        score = model.score(train_X, df.iloc[0:1000])<n>        accuracy.append(score)<n><n>    # Test the model<n>    for i in range(10):<n>        pbar.update(2)<n>        prediction = _make_kbest(model, classes)<n>        accuracy_max.append(accuracy

There are only 4 ways to add the 200 nickles in order to reach 56 cents: 4 quarters, 6 nickels, 1/2 quarter, and 1 nickel.  Since 2 quarters and 2 nickels weighs more than 4 quarters, the amount we must be using is six nickels and one quarter. It takes 15 minutes to shape the dough and 2 hours to proof.  The bread takes 30 minutes to bake and 15 minutes to cool.  If the bakery opens at 6:00 am, what is the latest time the head baker can make it to the store to start working?<n>Output: 2<n><n>Input: Geric had twice as many bills as Kyla who has 2 fewer bills than Jessa.  After giving 3 bills to Geric, Jessa has 7 bills left. How many bills did Geric have at the beginning?<n>Output: 16<n><n>Input:Where is a bay always found? Choices:  A: lake B: manhattan C: shoreline D: coastal area E: los angeles<n>Output:		D<n><n>Input:What is always considered to be one of the most expensive hobbies in the the united states? Choices: A: fishing B: hunting C: golf D: horseback riding E: skiing<n>Output:E<n><n>Input:Which sport has a team of 15 members, including players, mascots, and trainers? Choices: A. baseball B. cricket C. football D. soccer E. wrestling<n>Output:C<n><n>Input:Name a food that is considered a delicasy in italy? Choices: A) Pizza B) Spaghetti and Meatballs C) Gelato D) Chicken Parmesan E) Gelato<n>Output:C<n>```<n><n>#### SOLUTION<n>```<n># -*- coding: utf-8 -*-<n>import sys<n><n>import argparse<n>import numpy as np<n><n>class Solution(object):<n>    def myPow(self,A,B):<n>        """<n>    :rtype: A^B<n>        """<n>        return pow(A,B,(1+1)/(B+1))<n><n>    def myPln(self,input, A):<n>        """<n><n>        :param input: input array<n>        :rtype: array<n>        :param A: scalar value <n>        """<n>        resultList = []<n>        while(input.__len__()>0):<n>            list = [int(i)/A for i in sorted(input)][::-1]<n>            for i in list:<n>                resultList.append(i)<n>                input = input[i::-1]<n>                A = self.myPow(self.myPow(A, self.myPow('3',self.myPow('4',self.myPw('3',A)) ))  ,self.myPow("2",A))<n>            return resultList,A<n><n>    def myCal(self,num):<n>        """<n>        :param num<n>        :rtype int<n>        """<n>        n = int(num)<n>        if n==0:<n>            return 0<n>        elif n%2==0:<n>            #return 1-((num/2.)**2)<n>            return n // 2<n>        elif n%3
